<paragraph id="8BAE36A76E11FFEA48F7639F117F938B" blockId="38.[151,773,1191,1215]" box="[151,773,1191,1215]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Type-species: 
<taxonomicName id="4C114D246E11FFEA4948639F1008938B" authority="Muller, 1776" authorityName="Muller" authorityYear="1776" box="[296,626,1191,1215]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Halosphaeriaceae" genus="Amphitrite" kingdom="Fungi" order="Microascales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="cristata">
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E11FFEA4948639F1392938A" box="[296,488,1191,1215]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Amphitrite cristata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF804B566E11FFEA498F639F1008938B" author="Muller, O. F." box="[495,626,1191,1215]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" refId="ref44803" refString="Muller, O. F. (1776) Zoologicae Danicae Prodromus, seu Animalium Daniae et Norvegiae indigenarum characteres, nomina et synonyma imprimis popularium. Hallageriis. Havniae [Copenhagen], 282 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 13268" type="book" year="1776">Müller, 1776</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by monotypy.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30B652C6E11FFEA48F763D5102391EF" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BAE36A76E11FFEA48F763D5102391EF" blockId="38.[151,1437,1261,2043]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E11FFEA48F763D513689233" bold="true" box="[151,274,1261,1287]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
(after 
<bibRefCitation id="EF804B566E11FFEA493B63D51024923C" author="Hutchings, P. &amp; Nogueira, J. M. N. &amp; Carrerette, O." box="[347,606,1261,1288]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 64" refId="ref42972" refString="Hutchings, P., Nogueira, J. M. N. &amp; Carrerette, O. (2021 b) Terebellidae Johnston, 1846. In: Schmidt-Rhaesa, A. Hr., Beutel, R. G., Glaubrecht, M., Kristensen, N. P., Prendini, L., Purschke, G., Richter, S., Westheide, W. &amp; Leschen, R. Z. E. (Ed.), Handbook of Zoology. A Natural History of the Phyla of the Animal Kingdom. Walter de Gruyter &amp; Co, Berlin, pp. 1 - 64." type="book chapter" year="2021">
Hutchings 
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E11FFEA49B563D610779233" box="[469,525,1261,1287]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">et al.</emphasis>
2021b
</bibRefCitation>
). Transverse prostomium attached to dorsal surface of upper lip; basal part as a thick crest, eyespots sometimes present; distal part shelf-like. Buccal tentacles all uniformly cylindrical. Peristomium restricted to lips; upper lip relatively short, hood-like; lower lip swollen, cushion-like and mid-ventral. Segment I reduced dorsally, with pair of lobes of variable size and position; SG II–IV also with pairs of lobes of variable size and position, sometimes extending for a few more segments. Anterior segments highly glandular ventrally, with discrete, smooth to slightly corrugated, rectangular to trapezoidal mid-ventral shields. One, two or three pairs of arborescent, pectinate or plumous branchiae from SG II, typically two pairs, on SG II and III, less typically a single pair, and rarely 3 pairs. Conical to rectangular notopodia beginning on SG IV, typically extending for 17 segments, until SG XX; notochaetae all distally winged, frequently broadly-winged. Neuropodia beginning on SG V, as low ridges in conjunction with notopodia and short pinnules posteriorly; neurochaetae as long-handled avicular uncini, at least on anterior neuropodia, frequently until SG X or end of notopodia, then short-handled; uncini in partial to completely intercalated double rows on SG XI–XX, in a face-to-face arrangement. Nephridial papillae present on SG III, genital papillae on a variable number of segments, usually on SG VI–VII, posterior and dorsal to notopodia. Pygidium smooth to slightly crenulated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30B652C6E11FFEB48A761DD13EC96C1" lastPageId="39" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BAE36A76E11FFEB48A761DD13EC96C1" blockId="38.[151,1437,1261,2043]" lastBlockId="39.[151,1437,151,501]" lastPageId="39" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E11FFEA48A761DD134191CB" bold="true" box="[199,315,1765,1791]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Remarks.</emphasis>
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C114D246E11FFEA49A261DE138691CB" authorityName="Malmgren" authorityYear="1866" box="[450,508,1766,1791]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Pista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E11FFEA49A261DE138691CB" box="[450,508,1766,1791]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Pista</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably the most problematic one within the 
<taxonomicName id="4C114D246E11FFEA4C5161DD16C191CB" authorityName="Johnston" authorityYear="1846" box="[1073,1211,1765,1791]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="family">Terebellidae</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E11FFEA4CA361DE169D91CB" box="[1219,1255,1766,1791]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">s.s.</emphasis>
The main issue concerns the diagnostic characters of the type species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C114D246E11FFEA4A9C603216669010" authority="(Muller, 1776)" baseAuthorityName="Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" box="[764,1052,1801,1828]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Halosphaeriaceae" genus="Amphitrite" kingdom="Fungi" order="Microascales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="cristata">
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E11FFEA4A9C603211149017" box="[764,878,1802,1827]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. cristata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF804B566E11FFEA4B1C603116699010" author="Muller, O. F." box="[892,1043,1801,1828]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" refId="ref44803" refString="Muller, O. F. (1776) Zoologicae Danicae Prodromus, seu Animalium Daniae et Norvegiae indigenarum characteres, nomina et synonyma imprimis popularium. Hallageriis. Havniae [Copenhagen], 282 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 13268" type="book" year="1776">Müller, 1776</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. This species was reported around the world (
<bibRefCitation id="EF804B566E11FFEA49756015101A9073" author="Hutchings, P. &amp; Lavesque, N." box="[277,608,1837,1863]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="151 - 163" refId="ref42865" refString="Hutchings, P. &amp; Lavesque, N. (2020) I know who you are, but do others know? Why correct names are so important. Zoosymposia, 19, 151 - 163. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zoosymposia. 19.1.16" type="journal article" year="2020">Hutchings &amp; Lavesque 2020</bibRefCitation>
) because of: (1) a very brief original description and lack of type material, (2) a doubt concerning the number of pairs of branchiae and the arrangement of the branching filaments, and thus (3) confusion in several taxonomic keys. This species was described as having one pair of branchiae, while Malmgren who erected the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C114D246E11FFEA4A7460A210349087" authorityName="Malmgren" authorityYear="1866" box="[532,590,1946,1971]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Pista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E11FFEA4A7460A210349087" box="[532,590,1946,1971]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Pista</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and designated 
<taxonomicName id="4C114D246E11FFEA4B6360A2110F9087" baseAuthorityName="Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" box="[771,885,1946,1971]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Halosphaeriaceae" genus="Amphitrite" kingdom="Fungi" order="Microascales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="cristata">
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E11FFEA4B6360A2110F9087" box="[771,885,1946,1971]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. cristata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as the type species, stated that it has two pairs of branchiae. Some authors, as Jirkov &amp; Leontovich (2017), have discussed the validity of the generic boundaries, trying to understand the vague information contained in the original description of this species. Nevertheless, since the type material does not exist, and since these authors did not revise material from type locality, their comments are not very helpful. Fortunately, one of the present authors (M.H.L-M) has recently examined material from the type locality (Kristiansand fjord, 
<collectingCountry id="F30676376E10FFEB49B767E7104997CD" box="[471,563,223,249]" name="Norway" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Norway</collectingCountry>
) and will soon stabilize the taxonomic issues of this species by designating a 
<typeStatus id="54AA88056E10FFEB48F7663B12899629" box="[151,243,259,285]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">neotype</typeStatus>
, in order to give not only a full description of the species, but also morphological boundaries of the genus (Londoño-Mesa 
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E10FFEB4935661F138B9674" box="[341,497,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">et al. in prep.</emphasis>
). Based on his observation, 
<taxonomicName id="4C114D246E10FFEB4B5A661F11A99674" baseAuthorityName="Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" box="[826,979,295,320]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Pista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="cristata">
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E10FFEB4B5A661F11A99674" box="[826,979,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Pista cristata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by the presence of two pairs of pompom-like branchiae with tufts of branched filaments coming off the main stem (as followed by several authors: 
<bibRefCitation id="EF804B566E10FFEB489A6657139296BD" author="Nogueira, J. M. M. &amp; Harris, L. &amp; Hutchings, P. &amp; Fukuda, M. V." box="[250,488,367,393]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="1 - 26" refId="ref44915" refString="Nogueira, J. M. M., Harris, L., Hutchings, P. &amp; Fukuda, M. V. (2011) Four terebellines (Polychaeta, Terebellidae) with problematic taxonomic histories. Zootaxa, 2995 (1), 1 - 26. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2995.1.1" type="journal article" year="2011">
Nogueira 
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E10FFEB490B665713DF96BD" box="[363,421,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF804B566E10FFEB49966657116696BD" author="Mikac, B. &amp; Hutchings, P." box="[502,796,367,393]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="943 - 953" refId="ref44536" refString="Mikac, B. &amp; Hutchings, P. (2017) One new species of Pista Malmgren, 1866 (Annelida: Terebellidae) and one new species of Pistella Hartmann-Schroder, 1996 (Annelida: Terebellidae) from the Adriatic Sea (Mediterranean). Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom, 97 (05), 943 - 953. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / s 0025315417000868" type="journal article" year="2017">Mikac &amp; Hutchings 2017</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF804B566E10FFEB4B496657167796BD" author="Labrune, C. &amp; Lavesque, N. &amp; Bonifacio, P. &amp; Hutchings, P." box="[809,1037,367,393]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="71 - 83" refId="ref43387" refString="Labrune, C., Lavesque, N., Bonifacio, P. &amp; Hutchings, P. (2019) A new species of Pista Malmgren, 1866 (Annelida, Terebellidae) from the Western Mediterranean Sea. Zookeys, 838, 71 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 838.28634" type="journal article" year="2019">
Labrune 
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E10FFEB4BF0665711B096BD" box="[912,970,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF804B566E10FFEB4C7B6657175B96BD" author="Hutchings, P. &amp; Carrerette, O. &amp; Nogueira, J. M. N. N. &amp; Hourdez, S. &amp; Lavesque N." box="[1051,1313,367,393]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="60" refId="ref42915" refString="Hutchings, P., Carrerette, O., Nogueira, J. M. N. N., Hourdez, S. &amp; Lavesque N. (2021 a) The Terebelliformia- Recent developments and future directions. Diversity 13, 60. https: // doi. org / 10.3390 / d 13020060" type="journal article" year="2021">
Hutchings 
<emphasis id="B965EAB56E10FFEB4CF7665716B096BD" box="[1175,1226,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">et al</emphasis>
. 2021a
</bibRefCitation>
, b), by the absence of dorsal ridges on SG II–III, by short lateral lobes on SG I and well-developed lateral lobes on SG II–IV, by uncini short-necked, with long-handle posterior process restricted until SG VIII, and finally by genital papillae present on SG VI–VII.
</paragraph>
